# ---------------------------
# Data load
# ---------------------------
# Read CSV containing trust fund time series with columns:
# Program, Year, Income, Cost, Contributions, Reserves.
data <- read.csv("ss_fund.csv")

# ---------------------------
# Reshape to long format
# ---------------------------
# Convert wide metric columns into a long structure for plotting and modeling.
data_long <- data %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(Income, Cost, Contributions, Reserves),
    names_to = "Metric",
    values_to = "Value"
  )

# ---------------------------
# Numeric cleanup and scaling
# ---------------------------
# Remove thousands separators and convert to billions.
data_long$Value <- as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data_long$Value)) / 1e3

# ---------------------------
# Projection horizon
# ---------------------------
# Determine last observed year and create future years up to 2035 (if needed).
max_year <- max(data_long$Year, na.rm = TRUE)
future_years <- if (max_year < 2035) {
  data.frame(Year = seq(max_year + 1, 2035))
} else {
  data.frame(Year = integer(0))
}

# ---------------------------
# Projection helpers
# ---------------------------
# Polynomial projection for specified program/metric (degree controls curvature).
generate_projections <- function(program, metric, degree = 2) {
  df <- dplyr::filter(data_long, Program == program, Metric == metric)
  if (nrow(df) < (degree + 1) || nrow(future_years) == 0) {
    return(data.frame(Year = integer(0), Program = program, Metric = metric, Value = numeric(0)))
  }
  model <- lm(Value ~ poly(Year, degree), data = df)
  data.frame(
    Year    = future_years$Year,
    Program = program,
    Metric  = metric,
    Value   = predict(model, newdata = future_years)
  )
}

# Linear projection for specified program/metric (used for DI).
generate_linear_projections <- function(program, metric) {
  df <- dplyr::filter(data_long, Program == program, Metric == metric)
  if (nrow(df) < 2 || nrow(future_years) == 0) {
    return(data.frame(Year = integer(0), Program = program, Metric = metric, Value = numeric(0)))
  }
  model <- lm(Value ~ Year, data = df)
  data.frame(
    Year    = future_years$Year,
    Program = program,
    Metric  = metric,
    Value   = predict(model, newdata = future_years)
  )
}

# ---------------------------
# Build projections
# ---------------------------
# OASI uses modest polynomial trends; DI uses linear trends.
oasi_projections <- bind_rows(
  generate_projections("OASI", "Reserves",      degree = 3),
  generate_projections("OASI", "Income",        degree = 2),
  generate_projections("OASI", "Cost",          degree = 2),
  generate_projections("OASI", "Contributions", degree = 2)
)

di_projections <- bind_rows(
  generate_linear_projections("DI", "Reserves"),
  generate_linear_projections("DI", "Income"),
  generate_linear_projections("DI", "Cost"),
  generate_linear_projections("DI", "Contributions")
)

# Combine historical and projected values.
data_combined <- bind_rows(data_long, oasi_projections, di_projections)

# ---------------------------
# Plot
# ---------------------------
# Lines for historical values and projections; color/linetype encodes metric.
# Facet separates OASI and DI; y-scales are free by panel.
ggplot(data_combined, aes(x = Year, y = Value, color = Metric, linetype = Metric)) +
  geom_line(
    data = dplyr::filter(data_combined, Year <= max_year),
    linewidth = 1
  ) +
  geom_line(
    data = dplyr::filter(data_combined, Year > max_year),
    linewidth = 1
  ) +
  facet_grid(factor(Program, levels = c("OASI", "DI")) ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(min(data_long$Year, na.rm = TRUE), 2035, by = 5)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_number(suffix = "B")) +
  labs(
    title    = "OASI and DI Trust Fund: Historical Data and Projections (Through 2035)",
    x        = "Year",
    y        = "Value (Billions)",
    color    = "Metric",
    linetype = "Metric"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    strip.text.y    = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12),
    axis.text.x     = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)
  )

# ---------------------------
# Package citations
# ---------------------------
# Create a BibTeX file of citations for all loaded packages and print to console.
pkgs <- sort(unique(c(
  "corrplot","eia","EnvStats","fitdistrplus","fpp3","fredr","ggpattern","ggrepel",
  "grid","gridExtra","gtools","kableExtra","knitr","latex2exp","lpSolveAPI","MASS",
  "magrittr","MCMCpack","metR","psych","readxl","ResourceSelection","tidyverse","viridis"
)))

# Print human-readable citations.
for (p in pkgs) {
  cat("\n\n---- Citation for package:", p, "----\n")
  print(utils::citation(p))
}

# Write BibTeX entries to file.
dir.create("results/diagnostics", recursive = TRUE, showWarnings = FALSE)
bib_entries <- unlist(lapply(pkgs, function(p) {
  cites <- utils::citation(p)
  out <- try(toBibtex(cites), silent = TRUE)
  if (inherits(out, "try-error")) character(0) else out
}), use.names = FALSE)
writeLines(bib_entries, con = file.path("results", "diagnostics", "R-packages.bib"))

2 DI as a Percent of OASDI

# ---------------------------
# Data: DI as a percent of OASDI (19832024)
# ---------------------------
data <- data.frame(
  Year = 1983:2024,
  DI_Percent = c(
    11.6, 8.8, 8.8, 8.8, 8.8, 8.7, 8.7, 9.7, 9.7, 9.7, 9.7, 15.2, 15.2, 15.2, 13.7, 13.7,
    13.7, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5,
    14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 19.1, 19.1, 19.1, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5, 14.5
  )
)

# ---------------------------
# Drift model (linear trend between first and last observed points)
# ---------------------------
# Extract first and last observed values and years.
first_point <- data$DI_Percent[1]
last_point  <- data$DI_Percent[nrow(data)]
first_year  <- data$Year[1]
last_year   <- data$Year[nrow(data)]

# Slope of the straight line connecting first and last observations.
drift_slope <- (last_point - first_point) / (last_year - first_year)

# Fitted drift (straight line) for every year.
data$Drift <- first_point + drift_slope * (data$Year - first_year)

# ---------------------------
# Plot: observed series and drift line
# ---------------------------
ggplot(data, aes(x = Year, y = DI_Percent)) +
  # Observed series
  geom_line(color = "blue", linewidth = 1.2) +
  # Linear drift model
  geom_line(aes(y = Drift), color = "darkred", linetype = "dotted", linewidth = 1) +
  labs(
    title = "DI as a Percent of OASDI Over Time (with Drift Model)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "DI Percent of OASDI"
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1983, 2024, by = 5)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 21), breaks = seq(0, 21, by = 3)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)
  )

# Max Taxable Earnings & National Average Wage Index

# Max taxable earnings (nominal) and CPI-based deflators
# ---------------------------

  rep(3000,14), rep(3600,4), rep(4200,4),

# ---------------------------
# Years and length checks
# ---------------------------
years <- 1937:2024
stopifnot(
  length(MaxTaxableEarnings) == length(years),
  length(cpi_values) == length(years)
)

# ---------------------------
# Inflation adjustment (2024 dollars)
# ---------------------------
Inflation_Adjusted_Earnings <- MaxTaxableEarnings * cpi_values

# ---------------------------
# Assemble data frame
# ---------------------------
data <- data.frame(
  Year = years,
  Max_Taxable_Earnings = MaxTaxableEarnings,
  Inflation_Adjusted_Earnings = Inflation_Adjusted_Earnings
)

# ---------------------------
# Plot: nominal vs. 2024-dollar max taxable earnings
# ---------------------------
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)
library(scales)

# Long format for a clean legend
data_long <- data %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(Max_Taxable_Earnings, Inflation_Adjusted_Earnings),
    names_to = "Series",
    values_to = "EarningsUSD"
  )

ggplot(data_long, aes(x = Year, y = EarningsUSD, color = Series, linetype = Series)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  labs(
    title = "Max Taxable Earnings (Nominal) vs. Inflation-Adjusted (2024 Dollars)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Earnings (USD)",
    color = NULL,
    linetype = NULL
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_dollar(accuracy = 1)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = c(0.05, 0.95),
    legend.justification = c(0, 1),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = alpha("white", 0.7), color = NA)
  )

# Tax Rates

# ---------------------------
# Load and prepare tax rate data
# ---------------------------

# Read CSV containing tax rates by component (e.g., OASI, DI, Total) and by worker type (e.g., .SE suffix for self-employed)
data <- read.csv("tax_rates.csv")

# Reshape wide columns to long format, derive line type (employed vs self-employed) and color grouping (OASI/DI/Total)
data_long <- data %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = -Year,                 # Keep Year; gather all other columns
    names_to = "Variable",        # Column for original variable names
    values_to = "Value"           # Column for numeric values
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    # Self-employed indicated by ".SE" suffix in the variable name
    LineType = ifelse(grepl("\\.SE$", Variable), "Self-Employed", "Employed"),
    # Color groups by program/component label embedded in the variable name
    ColorGroup = case_when(
      grepl("OASI",  Variable) ~ "OASI",
      grepl("DI",    Variable) ~ "DI",
      grepl("Total", Variable) ~ "Total",
      TRUE ~ "Other"
    )
  )

# ---------------------------
# Plot: time series of tax rates
# ---------------------------
ggplot(data_long, aes(x = Year, y = Value, color = ColorGroup, linetype = LineType)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  labs(
    title   = "Social Security Tax Rates Over Time",
    x       = "Year",
    y       = "Tax Rate (%)",
    color   = "Tax Component",
    linetype = "Type"
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    limits = c(1937, 2024),
    breaks = seq(1940, 2024, by = 10)
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "top",
    legend.title    = element_text(size = 12),
    plot.title      = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold")
  )

# Maximum Tax by Year over Time

# ---------------------------
# Historical tax rates, taxable maximum, and CPI multipliers (to 2024 USD)
# ---------------------------
historical_data <- data.frame(
  Year = 1937:2024,
  # EmployeeRate is defined here as the employee-side OASDI rate.
  # The vector is halved (/2) to convert combined rates to the employee share.
  EmployeeRate = c(
    rep(0.02, 13), rep(0.03, 4), rep(0.04, 3), rep(0.045, 2), 0.05, 0.06, 0.06, 0.0625, rep(0.0725, 3),
    0.077, 0.078, 0.076, 0.084, 0.084, 0.092, 0.092, 0.097, rep(0.099, 4), 0.101, 0.1016, 0.1016,
    0.107, 0.108, 0.108, rep(0.114, 4), 0.1212, 0.1212, rep(0.124, 21), 0.104, 0.104, rep(0.124, 12)
  ) / 2,
  # Nominal maximum taxable earnings by year
  MaxTaxableEarnings = c(
    rep(3000, 14), rep(3600, 4), rep(4200, 4),
    rep(4800, 7), rep(6600, 2), rep(7800, 4),
    9000, 10800, 13200, 14100, 15300, 16500, 17700,
    22900, 25900, 29700, 32400, 35700, 37800,
    39600, 42000, 43800, 45000, 48000, 51300,
    53400, 55500, 57600, 60600, 61200, 62700,
    65400, 68400, 72600, 76200, 80400, 84900,
    87000, 87900, 90000, 94200, 97500, 102000,
    106800, 106800, 106800, 110100, 113700, 117000,
    118500, 118500, 127200, 128400, 132900, 137700,
    142800, 147000, 160200, 168600
  ),
  # CPI multipliers to convert nominal dollars in each year to 2024 dollars (2024 = 1.0)
  CPI = c(
    21.67673611, 22.13794326, 22.45647482, 22.29607143, 21.23435374, 19.15,
    18.04306358, 17.73551136, 17.34138889, 16.0074359, 13.99753363, 12.95207469,
    13.11533613, 12.95207469, 12.00557692, 11.7790566, 11.69082397, 11.60390335,
    11.64720149, 11.47591912, 11.10836299, 10.80086505, 10.7266323, 10.54543919,
    10.43963211, 10.33592715, 10.20081699, 10.06919355, 9.909365079, 9.634104938,
    9.345658683, 8.969683908, 8.505313351, 8.044974227, 7.707283951, 7.467583732,
    7.030292793, 6.331541582, 5.801951673, 5.485852373, 5.150907591, 4.7875,
    4.299517906, 3.788167476, 3.433938394, 3.234663212, 3.133985944, 3.004282964,
    2.900975836, 2.848038321, 2.747755282, 2.638588335, 2.517298387, 2.388255547,
    2.29181351, 2.224839629, 2.16017301, 2.106241565, 2.048195538, 1.98945188,
    1.94482866, 1.915, 1.873619448, 1.812688734, 1.762535291, 1.735102835,
    1.696440217, 1.652435151, 1.59828469, 1.548338294, 1.505459579, 1.449794011,
    1.454970471, 1.431490076, 1.387687329, 1.359552079, 1.339925394, 1.31853626,
    1.316973044, 1.300566233, 1.2734375, 1.243075661, 1.220952292, 1.206073158,
    1.151954091, 1.066597188, 1.024427145, 1
  )
)

# ---------------------------
# Derived series
# ---------------------------
historical_data <- historical_data %>%
  mutate(
    # Maximum employee-side tax in nominal dollars
    # (For combined employee+employer, multiply EmployeeRate by 2.)
    RawMaxTax = MaxTaxableEarnings * EmployeeRate,
    # Convert nominal maximum employee tax into 2024 dollars
    InflationAdjustedMaxTax = RawMaxTax * CPI
  )

# ---------------------------
# Plot: nominal vs inflation-adjusted maximum employee tax
# ---------------------------
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)

ggplot(historical_data, aes(x = Year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = RawMaxTax, color = "Raw Max Tax"), linewidth = 1) +
  geom_line(aes(y = InflationAdjustedMaxTax, color = "Inflation-Adjusted Max Tax"),
            linewidth = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(
    title = "Max Social Security Employee Tax Over Time (Nominal vs 2024 Dollars)",
    x     = "Year",
    y     = "Maximum Tax (USD)",
    color = "Series"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = label_dollar(accuracy = 1)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1940, 2024, by = 10)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16, face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "top"
  )

3 Individual Retirement Considerations

# ---------------------------
# Data ingest
# ---------------------------
# Expected columns (names and units):
#   Income : average annual covered earnings in thousands of USD
#   Age    : claiming/retirement age (e.g., 6280)
#   PIA    : Primary Insurance Amount in thousands of USD
pia_data <- read_csv("PIA.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

# ---------------------------
# Column validation / optional rename
# ---------------------------
# If the file uses different column names, uncomment and map them here.
# Example:
# pia_data <- pia_data %>%
#   rename(
#     Income = AvgCoveredEarnings_kUSD,
#     Age    = RetAge,
#     PIA    = PIA_kUSD
#   )

# Minimal structural checks: required columns present and numeric
required_cols <- c("Income", "Age", "PIA")
stopifnot(all(required_cols %in% names(pia_data)))

# Coerce to numeric if read as character (defensive parsing)
pia_data <- pia_data %>%
  mutate(
    Income = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(Income)),
    Age    = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(Age)),
    PIA    = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(PIA))
  )

# Remove any rows with missing or non-finite values after coercion
pia_data <- pia_data %>% filter(is.finite(Income), is.finite(Age), is.finite(PIA))

# ---------------------------
# Plot: PIA surface by income and age
# ---------------------------
# Heatmap (geom_tile) shows the PIA level. Contours provide isolines of equal PIA.
# metR::geom_text_contour overlays numeric labels along the contour lines.
ggplot(pia_data, aes(x = Income, y = Age, z = PIA)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = PIA), alpha = 0.9) +
  geom_contour(color = "black", binwidth = 0.5, linewidth = 0.3) +
  geom_text_contour(
    aes(label = after_stat(level)),
    binwidth = 0.5,
    size = 3
  ) +
  scale_fill_viridis(
    name = "PIA ($000s)",
    option = "viridis",
    direction = -1
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(
    breaks = seq(10, 160, by = 10),
    name   = "Average Annual Covered Earnings (in $000s)"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = seq(62, 80, by = 1),
    expand = expansion(mult = c(0.02, 0.02))
  ) +
  labs(
    title    = "Social Security Primary Insurance Amount (PIA) by Retirement Age and Income",
    subtitle = "Assumes full career covered earnings; delayed claiming raises PIA until age 70",
    caption  = "PIA measured in thousands of dollars; stylized contours assist comparison across ages and earnings."
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13) +
  theme(
    plot.title   = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),
    legend.position = "right",
    axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(r = 10)),
    axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10))
  )

4 Set Seed

# For exact replication purposes
set.seed(42)

5 Read Data

5.1 3-Month TBill Compounding Factor by Year

5.2 Social Security Cumulative Pay-In

# ---------------------------
# Data ingest
# ---------------------------
# SSPaidIn.csv must contain at least two numeric columns:
#   - Max     : maximum taxable earnings (or paid-in amount) per year
#   - Average : average taxable earnings (or paid-in amount) per year
# 87 annual rows are expected to align with the sampling loop below.
SSA <- read.csv("SSPaidIn.csv", check.names = TRUE)

# 2023dollars.csv must contain a single numeric column (Dollars2023)
# with 52 entries, used to convert 35-year sums into 2023 dollars.
inf <- read.csv("2023dollars.csv", check.names = TRUE)

# ---------------------------
# Basic structure checks (defensive)
# ---------------------------
stopifnot(all(c("Max", "Average") %in% names(SSA)))
stopifnot(is.numeric(SSA$Max), is.numeric(SSA$Average))
stopifnot(nrow(SSA) >= 87)   # expects at least 87 annual observations
stopifnot("Dollars2023" %in% names(inf), is.numeric(inf$Dollars2023))
stopifnot(length(inf$Dollars2023) >= 52)  # expects at least 52 conversion factors

# ---------------------------
# Element-wise triangular sampling by year
# ---------------------------
# For each of 87 years, draw one sample from a triangular distribution
# with support [0, Max] and mode at Average. This yields a plausible
# synthetic paid-in amount per year centered on the historical average
# while respecting the statutory maximum.
SSMax   <- SSA$Max
SSAvg   <- SSA$Average
SSSamp  <- numeric(87)

# Optional reproducibility (uncomment to fix draws)
# set.seed(20250301)

for (i in seq_len(87)) {
  SSSamp[i] <- rtri(
    n    = 1,
    min  = 0,
    mode = SSAvg[i],
    max  = SSMax[i]
  )
}

# ---------------------------
# Rolling 35-year sums across the 87-year series
# ---------------------------
# Construct 52 overlapping career-length windows (35 years each).
# Window t spans indices [t, t+34]. For t = 1..52, the last window ends at 87.
SSMaxF  <- numeric(52)
SSAvgF  <- numeric(52)
SSSampF <- numeric(52)

idx <- 1
for (i in 36:87) {             # i marks the end of the window
  start <- idx                 # start index of the 35-year window
  end   <- idx + 34            # end index of the 35-year window (inclusive)
  SSMaxF[idx]  <- sum(SSMax[start:end],   na.rm = TRUE)
  SSAvgF[idx]  <- sum(SSAvg[start:end],   na.rm = TRUE)
  SSSampF[idx] <- sum(SSSamp[start:end],  na.rm = TRUE)
  idx <- idx + 1
}

# ---------------------------
# Convert each 35-year sum into 2023 dollars
# ---------------------------
# Multiply each 35-year sum by the corresponding CPI/deflator factor.
# Assumes inf$Dollars2023[1:52] are aligned with the 52 windows above.
myss <- data.frame(
  SSMax     = SSMaxF  * inf$Dollars2023[1:52],
  SSAvg     = SSAvgF  * inf$Dollars2023[1:52],
  SSSample  = SSSampF * inf$Dollars2023[1:52]
)

# ---------------------------
# Output
# ---------------------------
# myss contains inflation-adjusted 35-year aggregates for:
#   - SSMax    : summed statutory maximums (per window) in 2023 dollars
#   - SSAvg    : summed historical averages (per window) in 2023 dollars
#   - SSSample : summed simulated draws (per window) in 2023 dollars
myss

5.3 Social Security Annual Payout

# ---------------------------------------
# Read payout inputs (52 overlapping 35-year windows)
# ---------------------------------------
SSR      <- read.csv("SSpayout.csv", check.names = TRUE)  # expects 52 rows
SSMaxR   <- SSR$Max
SSAvgR   <- SSR$Average

# Defensive checks: align with inflation vector and prior myss object
stopifnot(length(SSMaxR) == 52, length(SSAvgR) == 52)
stopifnot(exists("inf"), "Dollars2023" %in% names(inf), length(inf$Dollars2023) >= 52)
stopifnot(exists("myss"))  # created in the prior step

# ---------------------------------------
# Triangular sampling for each window t = 1..52
# ---------------------------------------
# For each 35-year window, draw one sample in [0, Max] with mode at Average.
# (Optional) set.seed(...) for reproducibility before sampling.
SSSampR <- vapply(
  X = seq_len(52),
  FUN = function(i) rtri(1, min = 0, mode = SSAvgR[i], max = SSMaxR[i]),
  FUN.VALUE = numeric(1)
)

# ---------------------------------------
# Convert to 2023 dollars and attach to myss
# ---------------------------------------
# Multiply each window's nominal amount by the corresponding 2023-dollar factor.
myss$SSMaxPayout     <- SSMaxR   * inf$Dollars2023[1:52]
myss$SSAvgPayout     <- SSAvgR   * inf$Dollars2023[1:52]
myss$SSSamplePayout  <- SSSampR  * inf$Dollars2023[1:52]

# Return the augmented data frame
myss

6 Descriptives

# ---------------------------------------
# Descriptive statistics table with IQR and APA-ready formatting
# Expects: 
#   - psych::describe(), knitr, kableExtra already attached upstream
#   - df CSV has at least 25 columns; non-numerics will be coerced
# ---------------------------------------

# 1) Read data
df <- read.csv("finalscores1029.csv", check.names = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# 2) Select analysis columns (first 25) and ensure numeric
dat <- df[, 1:25, drop = FALSE]

# Coerce non-numeric columns to numeric (safely; non-convertible -> NA)
dat[] <- lapply(dat, function(x) {
  if (is.numeric(x)) return(x)
  suppressWarnings(as.numeric(x))
})

# 3) Descriptive statistics (psych::describe returns one row per variable)
#    Includes min, median, mean, sd, max, etc.
desc <- psych::describe(dat)

# 4) Interquartile range (IQR) for each variable
iqr_vals <- apply(dat, 2, IQR, na.rm = TRUE)

# 5) Assemble formatted summary table
summary_table <- data.frame(
  Variable   = rownames(desc),
  Min        = round(desc$min,    2),
  Median     = round(desc$median, 2),
  `Mean (SD)`= sprintf("%.2f (%.2f)", desc$mean, desc$sd),
  Max        = round(desc$max,    2),
  IQR        = round(iqr_vals,    2),
  row.names  = NULL,
  check.names = FALSE
)

# 6) Render (auto-detect LaTeX vs HTML for Rmd)
fmt <- if (knitr::is_latex_output()) "latex" else "html"

summary_table %>%
  kbl(
    caption   = "Summary Statistics for Evaluation Scores (Including IQR)",
    col.names = c("Variable", "Min", "Median", "Mean (SD)", "Max", "IQR"),
    format    = fmt,
    booktabs  = TRUE,
    align     = "lccccr"
  ) %>%
  kableExtra::kable_styling(
    bootstrap_options = c("striped", "condensed", "hover", "responsive"),
    full_width = FALSE, 
    position   = "center"
  )

6.1 Boxplots

# ---------------------------------------
# Reshape LLM-by-construct columns and plot score distributions
# Expects upstream:
#   - df (data.frame) loaded (e.g., from "finalscores1029.csv")
#   - tidyverse (dplyr, tidyr), ggplot2, ggpattern attached
# ---------------------------------------

# Canonical construct and LLM identifiers
constructs  <- c("ICB", "T", "E", "S", "AF", "PV")         # six policy constructs
llm_ids     <- 1:4                                          # four LLM columns per construct
llm_labels  <- c("ChatGPT", "Claude", "Gemini", "Copilot")  # legend labels

# ---------------------------------------
# Identify present score columns in df
# ---------------------------------------
# Columns are expected to be named like "ICB1", "ICB2", ..., "PV4".
# Only keep columns that actually exist in df; always include "COA" for reference.
target_cols <- unlist(lapply(constructs, function(con) {
  paste0(con, llm_ids)
}))
target_cols <- target_cols[target_cols %in% names(df)]
target_cols <- c("COA", target_cols[target_cols != "COA"])
stopifnot(length(target_cols) > 1)  # at least COA + one score column

# ---------------------------------------
# Subset and reshape to long format
# ---------------------------------------
df_subset <- df[, target_cols, drop = FALSE]

df_long <- df_subset |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols      = -COA,
    names_to  = "Metric",
    values_to = "Score"
  )

# Parse construct and LLM id from names like "ICB3"
df_long$Construct <- sub("([A-Z]+)\\d+", "\\1", df_long$Metric)
df_long$LLM_ID    <- as.integer(sub("[A-Z]+(\\d+)", "\\1", df_long$Metric))
df_long$LLM       <- factor(df_long$LLM_ID, levels = 1:4, labels = llm_labels)

# Keep finite scores only; drop missing or non-numeric
df_long_filtered <- df_long[is.finite(df_long$Score), , drop = FALSE]

# Ensure a consistent Construct order (top-to-bottom in plot if needed)
df_long_filtered$Construct <- factor(
  df_long_filtered$Construct,
  levels = constructs
)

# ---------------------------------------
# Boxplot with color+pattern encodings to preserve readability in grayscale/print
# ---------------------------------------
p <- ggplot(df_long_filtered, aes(x = Score, y = Construct, fill = LLM, pattern = LLM)) +
  geom_boxplot_pattern(
    position        = position_dodge(width = 0.75),
    outlier.shape   = 21,
    outlier.fill    = "black",
    pattern_fill    = "white",
    pattern_colour  = "black",
    pattern_density = 0.5,
    pattern_spacing = 0.04,
    pattern_size    = 0.12
  ) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel1") +
  scale_pattern_manual(values = c(
    "ChatGPT" = "none",
    "Claude"  = "stripe",
    "Gemini"  = "crosshatch",
    "Copilot" = "weave"
  )) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-5, 5)) +
  labs(
    title   = "Distributions of LLM Evaluations by Construct",
    x       = "Score",
    y       = "Construct",
    fill    = "LLM",
    pattern = "LLM"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 16) +
  theme(
    plot.title      = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    aspect.ratio    = 1.0,
    strip.text      = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.text.y     = element_text(size = 14),
    axis.title.y    = element_text(size = 16),
    legend.key.size = unit(1.5, "cm"),
    legend.text     = element_text(size = 12)
  ) +
  guides(
    fill    = guide_legend(override.aes = list(pattern = c("none", "stripe", "crosshatch", "weave"))),
    pattern = guide_legend(override.aes = list(fill = scales::brewer_pal(palette = "Pastel1")(4)))
  )

# ---------------------------------------
# Save and display
# ---------------------------------------
# Large height accommodates six facets (one row) with readable labels and legend.
ggsave("llm_construct_distributions_taller.png", p, width = 20, height = 25, dpi = 300)

print(p)

7 Correlation Matrix

# --------------------------------------------------------------------
# Correlation analysis of LLM ratings by construct with colorblind-safe palettes
# Expects upstream:
#   - Packages already attached (e.g., readr, dplyr/tidyverse, corrplot, viridis)
#   - File "finalscores1029.csv" in working directory
# --------------------------------------------------------------------

# 1) Color palettes ---------------------------------------------------
# IBM design-inspired categorical palette (for corrplot gradient generation)
ibm_palette <- colorRampPalette(c(
  "#648FFF",  # blue
  "#785EF0",  # purple
  "#DC267F",  # magenta
  "#FE6100",  # orange
  "#FFB000",  # yellow
  "#00BFC4",  # teal
  "#009E73"   # green
))(100)

# Continuous palette for per-construct plots (viridis is colorblind-safe)
viridis_colors <- viridis::viridis(100)

# 2) Read and prepare rating data ------------------------------------
#    File contains columns such as ICB1..ICB4, T1..T4, ..., PV1..PV4
scores <- read.csv("finalscores1029.csv", check.names = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Expected rating columns (24 total: 6 constructs  4 models)
rating_cols <- c(
  paste0("ICB", 1:4),
  paste0("T",   1:4),
  paste0("E",   1:4),
  paste0("S",   1:4),
  paste0("AF",  1:4),
  paste0("PV",  1:4)
)

# Keep only rating columns that actually exist in the file
rating_cols <- rating_cols[rating_cols %in% names(scores)]
stopifnot(length(rating_cols) > 0)

rating_vars <- scores[, rating_cols, drop = FALSE]

# Coerce to numeric (non-numeric values become NA)
rating_vars[] <- lapply(rating_vars, function(x) {
  if (is.numeric(x)) return(x)
  suppressWarnings(as.numeric(x))
})

# 3) Correlation matrix (Spearman) -----------------------------------
#    Pairwise complete observations to retain as much data as possible
corr_matrix <- cor(rating_vars, method = "spearman", use = "pairwise.complete.obs")

# Preserve logical ordering by construct (ICB1..4, T1..4, ..., PV1..4)
ordered_vars <- rating_cols
corr_matrix_ordered <- corr_matrix[ordered_vars, ordered_vars]

# 4) Global correlation plot -----------------------------------------
#    Upper-triangular plot with circles; coefficients not printed in cells
corrplot::corrplot(
  corr_matrix_ordered,
  method   = "circle",
  type     = "upper",
  tl.col   = "black",
  tl.cex   = 0.6,     # smaller label text
  tl.srt   = 45,      # rotate labels
  cl.ratio = 0.2,
  cl.align = "r",
  addCoef.col = NULL, # do not draw numeric coefficients in cells
  col      = ibm_palette,
  diag     = FALSE,
  mar      = c(1, 1, 3, 3),
  title    = "Correlation Matrix of Social Security Reform Ratings (Spearman)"
)

# 5) Per-construct helper and list -----------------------------------
#    Returns the 44 correlation matrix for a given construct (e.g., ICB)
get_construct_correlations <- function(dat, construct) {
  cols <- grep(paste0("^", construct), names(dat), value = TRUE)
  cor(dat[, cols, drop = FALSE], use = "pairwise.complete.obs", method = "spearman")
}

constructs <- c("ICB", "T", "E", "S", "AF", "PV")

# 6) 32 panel PDF of per-construct correlations ---------------------
pdf("construct_correlation_plots.pdf", width = 10, height = 15)
par(mfrow = c(3, 2), mar = c(3, 3, 4, 2))
for (construct in constructs) {
  this_cor <- get_construct_correlations(rating_vars, construct)
  corrplot::corrplot(
    this_cor,
    method   = "color",
    type     = "full",
    tl.col   = "black",
    addCoef.col = "black",
    number.cex = 1.0,
    col      = viridis_colors,
    title    = paste("Correlations for", construct)
  )
}
dev.off()
## png 
##   2
# 7) Individual PDFs per construct -----------------------------------
for (construct in constructs) {
  pdf(paste0(construct, "_correlation_plot.pdf"), width = 8, height = 7)
  this_cor <- get_construct_correlations(rating_vars, construct)
  corrplot::corrplot(
    this_cor,
    method   = "color",
    type     = "full",
    tl.col   = "black",
    addCoef.col = "black",
    number.cex = 0.8,
    col      = viridis_colors,
    title    = paste("Correlations Among", construct, "Ratings")
  )
  dev.off()
}

# 8) Summary of construct-wise correlations --------------------------
#    Average, min, and max of the lower triangle for each construct's 44 matrix
construct_consistency <- data.frame(
  Construct      = character(),
  AvgCorrelation = numeric(),
  MinCorrelation = numeric(),
  MaxCorrelation = numeric(),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)

for (construct in constructs) {
  m <- get_construct_correlations(rating_vars, construct)
  vals <- m[lower.tri(m)]
  construct_consistency <- rbind(
    construct_consistency,
    data.frame(
      Construct      = construct,
      AvgCorrelation = mean(vals, na.rm = TRUE),
      MinCorrelation = min(vals, na.rm = TRUE),
      MaxCorrelation = max(vals, na.rm = TRUE)
    )
  )
}

8 Cohens Kappa

# --------------------------------------------------------------------
# Pairwise (weighted) Cohen's kappa across all LLM raters within each construct
# Expects upstream:
#   - rating_vars: data.frame with columns ICB1..ICB4, T1..T4, ..., PV1..PV4
#   - psych::cohen.kappa() available (package already attached upstream)
# Notes:
#   - Converts numeric ratings to ordered factors to reflect ordinality.
#   - Drops incomplete cases pairwise before computing kappa.
#   - Returns both unweighted (nominal) and weighted (ordinal) kappas.
# --------------------------------------------------------------------

# Function to compute all pairwise kappas for columns matching a prefix (e.g., "ICB")
compute_kappas <- function(df, var_prefix) {
  # Identify columns for the construct (e.g., ICB1..ICB4)
  cols <- grep(paste0("^", var_prefix), names(df), value = TRUE)
  if (length(cols) < 2) {
    return(data.frame(
      Construct = character(),
      Rater1 = character(),
      Rater2 = character(),
      Kappa = numeric(),
      WeightedKappa = numeric(),
      stringsAsFactors = FALSE
    ))
  }

  # All unique rater pairs
  combinations <- utils::combn(cols, 2, simplify = FALSE)

  # Compute kappas for each pair
  kappas <- lapply(combinations, function(pair) {
    r1 <- df[[pair[1]]]
    r2 <- df[[pair[2]]]

    # Coerce to ordered factors to respect ordinal scale (-5..+5 typical)
    # Keep original unique sorted levels present in the data
    all_levels <- sort(unique(stats::na.omit(c(r1, r2))))
    r1f <- factor(r1, levels = all_levels, ordered = TRUE)
    r2f <- factor(r2, levels = all_levels, ordered = TRUE)

    # Pairwise complete observations
    cc <- stats::complete.cases(r1f, r2f)
    r1c <- r1f[cc]
    r2c <- r2f[cc]

    # If not enough data to compute kappa, return NA row
    if (length(r1c) < 2 || length(unique(r1c)) < 2 || length(unique(r2c)) < 2) {
      return(data.frame(
        Construct = var_prefix,
        Rater1 = pair[1],
        Rater2 = pair[2],
        Kappa = NA_real_,
        WeightedKappa = NA_real_
      ))
    }

    # Compute Cohen's kappa (psych::cohen.kappa)
    # Returns both unweighted kappa and weighted.kappa (for ordinal agreement)
    k <- psych::cohen.kappa(cbind(r1c, r2c))

    data.frame(
      Construct = var_prefix,
      Rater1 = pair[1],
      Rater2 = pair[2],
      Kappa = unname(k$kappa),
      WeightedKappa = unname(k$weighted.kappa)
    )
  })

  do.call(rbind, kappas)
}

# Constructs to evaluate
constructs <- c("ICB", "T", "E", "S", "AF", "PV")

# Compute kappas for all constructs and bind
kappa_list <- lapply(constructs, function(cx) compute_kappas(rating_vars, cx))
kappa_all  <- do.call(rbind, kappa_list)

# Optional: tidy ordering and simple summary columns
kappa_all <- kappa_all |>
  dplyr::mutate(
    Raters = paste(Rater1, "vs", Rater2),
    Kappa = round(Kappa, 3),
    WeightedKappa = round(WeightedKappa, 3)
  ) |>
  dplyr::select(Construct, Raters, Kappa, WeightedKappa, Rater1, Rater2)

# Inspect in console
print(kappa_all)

9 Integer Goal Programming Approach to Policy Selection

9.1 Formulation

Formulation

9.2 Program

# Set a reproducible random seed for the entire script
set.seed(1234)

# Number of Monte Carlo repetitions (independent optimization runs)
num_reps <- 100

# Read COA goal data (expects 24 goal columns + 1 actuarial effect column + optional metadata)
# - strip.white trims whitespace in character fields
df <- read.csv("finalscores1029.csv", strip.white = TRUE)

# Accumulator for all selected COAs across all runs (one row per selected COA)
all_runs <- data.frame()

# Holder for the best (highest objective value) result per Nmax (portfolio-size cap)
best_by_nmax <- tibble(
  MaxCOAs = numeric(),
  ObjVal = numeric()
)

# Problem size: number of COAs (binary vars), number of goal columns used, and SS effect col index
num_coas <- 142
num_goals <- 24  # Only the first 24 goals are used for targets/deviations
ss_effect_col <- 25
total_vars <- num_coas + (2 * num_goals)  # x binaries + positive/negative deviations per goal

# Names for constructs and LLMs (used for labeling/diagnostics only)
construct_names <- c("ICB", "T", "E", "S", "AF", "PV", "SS_Effect")
llm_names <- c("Inara", "Claude", "Gemini", "Copilot")

# Loop over randomized optimization runs
for (i in 1:num_reps) {
  
  # Draw 7 construct weights from a Dirichlet (6 constructs + SS_Effect)
  # - These represent the relative importance of each construct for this run
  construct_weights <- as.vector(rdirichlet(1, rep(1, 7)))
  names(construct_weights) <- construct_names

  # Draw within-construct LLM weights: a separate Dirichlet() for each of 6 constructs
  # -  ~ Uniform(1,5) adds modest variability in rater emphasis per construct
  llm_weights_list <- lapply(1:6, function(x) as.vector(rdirichlet(1, runif(4, 1, 5))))
  flattened_llm_weights <- unlist(llm_weights_list)  # Length = 24 (6 constructs  4 LLMs)

  # Expand 6 construct weights to align with the 24 LLM-specific columns (4 per construct)
  expanded_construct_weights <- rep(construct_weights[1:6], each = 4)

  # Final 24 weights = construct weight  LLM weight (per construct-LLM cell)
  final_weights <- expanded_construct_weights * flattened_llm_weights

  # Complete weight vector: 24 multi-criteria columns + 1 SS_Effect construct
  weights <- c(final_weights, construct_weights["SS_Effect"])
  names(weights) <- c(colnames(df[, 1:num_goals]), "SS_Effect")

  # Randomize maximum number of COAs allowed (cardinality cap) in {1,,6}
  max_num_coas <- sample(1:6, 1)

  # Penalty  for negative deviations (goal shortfalls), drawn uniformly in [0.2, 0.7]
  lambda <- runif(1, 0.2, 0.7)

  # Create an empty LP with the appropriate number of variables
  lprec <- make.lp(0, total_vars)

  # Set COA decision variables (first num_coas columns) to binary
  set.type(lprec, columns = 1:num_coas, type = "binary")

  # Set deviation variables to real (non-negative by default), covering:
  #   - d_pos[1..num_goals] and d_neg[1..num_goals]
  set.type(lprec, columns = (num_coas + 1):total_vars, type = "real")

  # Add goal-equality constraints:
  # For each goal g:
  #   sum_i score(i,g) * x_i + d_pos[g] - d_neg[g] = target[g]
  targets <- rep(5, num_goals)
  for (g in 1:num_goals) {
    row <- numeric(total_vars)
    row[1:num_coas] <- df[, g]                  # Scores for goal g across COAs
    row[num_coas + g] <- 1                      # + positive deviation for goal g
    row[num_coas + num_goals + g] <- -1         # - negative deviation for goal g
    add.constraint(lprec, row, "=", targets[g])
  }

  # Portfolio-size constraint (cardinality-like):
  #   Sum of chosen COAs  max_num_coas, but privatization COAs (141142) count as 5 each
  limit_row <- numeric(total_vars)
  limit_row[1:140] <- 1
  limit_row[141:142] <- 5
  add.constraint(lprec, limit_row, "<=", max_num_coas)

  # Privatization exclusivity: at most one of COA 141 or 142 may be selected
  priv_row <- numeric(total_vars)
  priv_row[141:142] <- 1
  add.constraint(lprec, priv_row, "<=", 1)

  # Actuarial (SS_Effect) constraint: ensure the selected portfolio achieves  3.5
  ss_effect_row <- numeric(total_vars)
  ss_effect_row[1:num_coas] <- df[, ss_effect_col]
  add.constraint(lprec, ss_effect_row, ">=", 3.5)

  # Objective:
  #   Maximize (weighted multi-criteria score of selected COAs)
  #              * (sum of negative deviations across goals)
  goal_matrix <- as.matrix(df[, 1:num_goals]) %*% diag(weights[1:num_goals])
  obj <- rowSums(goal_matrix)                   # Per-COA weighted score
  full_obj <- numeric(total_vars)
  full_obj[1:num_coas] <- obj                   # Coefficients for x_i
  full_obj[(num_coas + 1):(num_coas + num_goals)] <- -lambda  # Penalize positive deviations (as coded)
  full_obj[(num_coas + num_goals + 1):total_vars] <- 0        # No penalty on negative deviations (as coded)

  set.objfn(lprec, full_obj)
  lp.control(lprec, sense = "max")              # Maximize the objective

  # Solve the model (status 0 = optimal)
  status <- solve(lprec)

  # Retrieve solution vector and identify selected COAs
  sol <- get.variables(lprec)
  selected_indices <- which(sol[1:num_coas] == 1)

  # If feasible and non-empty selection, assemble and store results
  if (status == 0 && length(selected_indices) > 0) {
    selected_COAs <- df[selected_indices, ]
    selected_COAs$COA_ID <- as.integer(rownames(df)[selected_indices])
    selected_COAs$WeightedScore <- obj[selected_indices]
    selected_COAs$ObjVal <- get.objective(lprec)
    selected_COAs$Run <- i
    selected_COAs$Lambda <- lambda
    selected_COAs$MaxCOAs <- max_num_coas

    # Add all weights (constructLLM + SS_Effect) as columns for traceability
    for (j in seq_along(weights)) {
      selected_COAs[[paste0("W_", names(weights)[j])]] <- weights[j]
    }

    # Aggregate LLM contributions across constructs and normalize
    llm_labels <- rep(llm_names, times = 6)
    llm_contributions <- tapply(final_weights, llm_labels, sum)
    llm_contributions <- llm_contributions / sum(final_weights)

    # Add LLM contribution diagnostics to the selected COAs
    for (llm in names(llm_contributions)) {
      selected_COAs[[paste0("LLMWeight_", llm)]] <- llm_contributions[llm]
    }

    # Append current runs selections to the master results data.frame
    all_runs <- bind_rows(all_runs, selected_COAs)

    # Update best-by-Nmax tracker (keep the single best per MaxCOAs)
    current_best <- best_by_nmax %>% filter(MaxCOAs == max_num_coas)
    if (nrow(current_best) == 0 || selected_COAs$ObjVal[1] > max(current_best$ObjVal, na.rm = TRUE)) {
      best_by_nmax <- best_by_nmax %>% filter(MaxCOAs != max_num_coas)
      best_by_nmax <- bind_rows(best_by_nmax, selected_COAs)
    }
  } else {
    # Log infeasibility or errors for this iteration
    cat(sprintf("Run %d infeasible or error\n", i))
  }
}

# Summarize results per run if any selections exist
if (nrow(all_runs) > 0) {
  summary_output <- all_runs %>%
    group_by(Run) %>%
    summarise(
      `Objective Value` = first(ObjVal),
      `Max COAs` = first(MaxCOAs),
      Lambda = first(Lambda),
      `COAs Selected` = paste(COA_ID, collapse = ", "),
      `Types Selected` = paste(unique(Type), collapse = ", "),
      `Weighted Scores` = paste(round(WeightedScore, 2), collapse = ", ")
    ) %>%
    arrange(desc(`Objective Value`))

  print(summary_output)

  # Average (normalized) LLM contributions across all runs
  llm_summary <- all_runs %>%
    dplyr::select(starts_with("LLMWeight_")) %>%
    summarise(across(everything(), mean, na.rm = TRUE))

  cat("\nAverage LLM Contributions Across Runs:\n")
  print(round(llm_summary, 4))
}

10 Convergence Analysis

# Compute within-Nmax (portfolio size cap) solution congruence using Jaccard similarity

# Step 1: collapse selections to unique COA sets per (MaxCOAs, Run)
congruence_scores <- all_runs %>%
  distinct() %>%                              # remove duplicate rows if any (e.g., repeated joins/prints)
  group_by(MaxCOAs, Run) %>%                  # group by portfolio-size cap and the specific run
  summarise(COA_Set = list(unique(COA_ID)),   # collect the set of selected COA IDs for each run
            .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(MaxCOAs) %>%                       # compute congruence within each Nmax separately
  summarise(
    Congruence = {
      runs <- COA_Set                         # list of COA ID vectors (one per run at this Nmax)
      n <- length(runs)                       # number of runs recorded for this Nmax
      if (n < 2) return(NA_real_)             # need at least two runs to compute pairwise similarity

      # Step 2: compute pairwise Jaccard similarity across all run pairs
      # J(A,B) = |A  B| / |A  B|
      scores <- combn(n, 2, function(idx) {   # iterate over all pairs of run indices
        a <- runs[[idx[1]]]                   # COA set for run i
        b <- runs[[idx[2]]]                   # COA set for run j
        intersect_len <- length(intersect(a, b))
        union_len <- length(union(a, b))
        if (union_len == 0) return(NA_real_)  # guard against empty unions (shouldn't happen if sets are non-empty)
        else return(intersect_len / union_len)
      })

      mean(scores, na.rm = TRUE)              # Step 3: average pairwise Jaccard to get congruence for this Nmax
    },
    NumRuns = n()                             # number of runs available for this Nmax
  )

# Display congruence summary by Nmax (average Jaccard and run counts)
print(congruence_scores)
##   MaxCOAs Congruence NumRuns
## 1       1  1.0000000      14
## 2       2  1.0000000      23
## 3       3  1.0000000      21
## 4       4  1.0000000      15
## 5       5  0.8529412      17
## 6       6  0.8492063      10
# Persist congruence results for downstream diagnostics/reporting
write.csv(congruence_scores, "congruence_by_nmax.csv", row.names = FALSE)
